// Forgejo WRITE tier - the middle of the read ⊂ write ⊂ admin chain (ward#240).
// `inherit` (cli-guard#160) pulls in every grant of the read tier (and its
// spec/base-url/auth singletons, which this file does not restate), then layers
// the two write-side convention verbs on top. The result is read + create/edit:
// a `ward-kdl-write` binary that can author content but never delete it - the
// delete leaf is still not compiled in (that is the admin tier).
//
// `restrict` is child-local under inherit, so the coily*-owner scope gate is
// re-declared here rather than inherited. See
// ../../../docs/ward-kdl/ward-kdl.forgejo.write.guardfile.md.
wrap ward-kdl-write ops forgejo {
    inherit "../ward-kdl-read/ward-kdl.forgejo.read.guardfile.kdl"
    // Scope gate: re-declared because restrict does not inherit (cli-guard#160).
    restrict owner matches coily*
    // write tier adds the two write-side convention verbs across every resource.
    can create *
    can edit *
}
